# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: carnot-cycle
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] Thermodynamic temperature is typically expressed using the Kelvin scale, on which the unit of measurement is the *kelvin* (unit symbol: K).
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] This unit is the same interval as the degree Celsius, used on the Celsius scale but the scales are offset so that 0 K on the Kelvin scale corresponds to absolute zero.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] For comparison, a temperature of 295 K corresponds to 21.85 °C and 71.33 °F.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] Another absolute scale of temperature is the Rankine scale, which is based on the Fahrenheit degree interval.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] Thermodynamic temperature can be defined in purely thermodynamic terms using the Carnot cycle.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] Thermodynamic temperature was rigorously defined historically long before particles such as atoms, molecules, and electrons were fully understood.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] The International System of Units (SI) specifies the absolute scale for measuring temperature, and the unit of measure *kelvin* (symbol: K) for specific values along the scale.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] A temperature interval of one degree Celsius is the same as one kelvin.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] Since the 2019 revision of the SI, the kelvin has been defined in relation to the *physical property* underlying thermodynamic temperature: the kinetic energy of atomic free particle motion.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] The revision fixed the Boltzmann constant at exactly 1.380649×10−23 J⋅K−1.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] The property that imbues material substances with a temperature can be readily understood by examining the ideal gas law, which relates, through the Boltzmann constant, how heat energy causes precisely defined changes in the pressure and temperature of certain gases.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] This is because monatomic gases like helium and argon behave kinetically like freely moving perfectly elastic and spherical billiard balls that move only in a specific subset of the possible motions that can occur in matter: that comprising the three *translational* degrees of freedom.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] The translational degrees of freedom are the familiar billiard ball-like movements along the *x*-, *y*-, and *z*-axes of 3D space (see *Fig.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] This is why the noble gases all have the same heat capacity per atom and why that value is lowest of all the gases.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] Molecules (two or more chemically bound atoms), however, have *internal structure* and therefore have additional *internal* degrees of freedom (see *Fig.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] 3*, below), which has the effect that molecules absorb more heat energy for any given rise in temperature than do the monatomic gases.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] Heat energy is born in all available degrees of freedom; this is in accordance with the equipartition theorem, so all available internal degrees of freedom have the same average energy as do their three external degrees of freedom.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] However, the property that gives all gases their pressure, which is the net force per unit area on a container arising from gas particles recoiling off it, is a function of the kinetic energy borne in the freely moving atoms' and molecules' three translational degrees of freedom.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] Fixing the Boltzmann constant at a specific value had the effect of precisely establishing the magnitude of the kelvin in terms of the average kinetic behavior of the noble gases.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] Moreover, the *starting point* of the thermodynamic temperature scale, absolute zero, was reaffirmed as the point at which *zero average kinetic energy* remains in a sample; the only remaining particle motion being that comprising random vibrations due to zero-point energy.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] The numerical zero of a temperature scale is not bound to the absolute zero of temperature.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] Nevertheless, some temperature scales have their numerical zero coincident with the absolute zero of temperature.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] Examples are the Kelvin temperature scale and the Rankine temperature scale.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] Other temperature scales have their numerical zero far from the absolute zero of temperature.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] Examples are the Celsius scale and the Fahrenheit scale.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] At the zero point of thermodynamic temperature, absolute zero, the particle constituents of matter have minimal motion and can become no colder.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] Absolute zero, which is a temperature of zero kelvins (0 K), precisely corresponds to −273.15 °C and −459.67 °F.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] Matter at absolute zero has no remaining transferable average kinetic energy and the only remaining particle motion is due to an ever-pervasive quantum mechanical phenomenon called ZPE (zero-point energy).
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] Temperature is generally expressed in absolute terms when scientifically examining temperature's interrelationships with certain other physical properties of matter such as its volume or pressure (see Gay-Lussac's law), or the wavelength of its emitted black-body radiation.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] Absolute temperature is also useful when calculating chemical reaction rates (see Arrhenius equation).
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] Though there have been many other temperature scales throughout history, there have been only two scales for measuring thermodynamic temperature which have absolute zero as their null point (0): The Kelvin scale and the Rankine scale.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] Throughout the scientific world where modern measurements are nearly always made using the International System of Units, thermodynamic temperature is measured using the Kelvin scale.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] The Rankine scale is part of English engineering units and finds use in certain engineering fields, particularly in legacy reference works.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] The Rankine scale uses the *degree Rankine* (symbol: °R) as its unit, which is the same magnitude as the degree Fahrenheit (symbol: °F).
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] A unit increment of one kelvin is exactly 1.8 times one degree Rankine; thus, to convert a specific temperature on the Kelvin scale to the Rankine scale, ***x* K = 1.8 *x* °R**, and to convert from a temperature on the Rankine scale to the Kelvin scale, ***x* °R = *x*/1.8 K**.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] Consequently, absolute zero is "0" for both scales, but the melting point of water ice (0 °C and 273.15 K) is 491.67 °R.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] To convert temperature *intervals* (a span or difference between two temperatures), the formulas from the preceding paragraph are applicable; for instance, an interval of 5 kelvins is precisely equal to an interval of 9 degrees Rankine.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] For 65 years, between 1954 and the 2019 revision of the SI, a temperature interval of one kelvin was defined as ⁠1/273.16⁠ of the temperature difference between the triple point of water and absolute zero.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] The net effect of this as well as later resolutions was twofold: 1) they defined absolute zero as precisely 0 K, and 2) they defined that the triple point of special isotopically controlled water called Vienna Standard Mean Ocean Water occurred at precisely 273.16 K and 0.01 °C.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] One effect of the aforementioned resolutions was that the melting point of water, while *very* close to 273.15 K and 0 °C, was not a defining value and was subject to refinement with more precise measurements.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] This shortcoming was addressed by the International Temperature Scale of 1990, or ITS‑90, which defined 13 additional points, from 13.8033 K, to 1,357.77 K.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] While definitional, ITS‑90 had—and still has—some challenges, partly because eight of its extrapolated values depend upon the melting or freezing points of metal samples, which must remain exceedingly pure lest their melting or freezing points be affected—usually depressed.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] The solution required that four physical constants, including the Boltzmann constant, be definitionally fixed.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] Assigning the Boltzmann constant a precisely defined value had no practical effect on modern thermometry except for the most exquisitely precise measurements.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] Afterwards, by defining the Boltzmann constant as exactly 1.380649×10−23 J/K, the 0.37 ppm uncertainty was transferred to the triple point of water, which became an experimentally determined value of 273.1600±0.0001 K (0.0100±0.0001 °C).
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] Notwithstanding the 2019 revision, water triple-point cells continue to serve in modern thermometry as exceedingly precise calibration references at 273.16 K and 0.01 °C.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] Moreover, the triple point of water remains one of the 14 calibration points comprising ITS‑90, which spans from the triple point of hydrogen (13.8033 K) to the freezing point of copper (1,357.77 K), which is a nearly hundredfold range of thermodynamic temperature.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] The thermodynamic temperature of any *bulk quantity* of a substance (a statistically significant quantity of particles) is directly proportional to the mean average kinetic energy of a specific kind of particle motion known as *translational motion*.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] These simple movements in the three *x*-, *y*-, and *z*-axes dimensions of space means the particles move in the three spatial *degrees of freedom*.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] This particular form of kinetic energy is sometimes referred to as *kinetic temperature*.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] Translational motion is but one form of heat energy and is what gives gases not only their temperature, but also their pressure and the vast majority of their volume.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] This relationship between the temperature, pressure, and volume of gases is established by the ideal gas law's formula *pV* = *nRT* and is embodied in the gas laws.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] Though the kinetic energy borne exclusively in the three translational degrees of freedom comprise the thermodynamic temperature of a substance, molecules, as can be seen in *Fig.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] 3*, can have other degrees of freedom, all of which fall under three categories: bond length, bond angle, and rotational.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] All three additional categories are not necessarily available to all molecules, and even for molecules that *can* experience all three, some can be "frozen out" below a certain temperature.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] The relationship of kinetic energy, mass, and velocity is given by the formula *E*k = ⁠1/2⁠*mv*2.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] Accordingly, particles with one unit of mass moving at one unit of velocity have precisely the same kinetic energy, and precisely the same temperature, as those with four times the mass but half the velocity.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] At any one instant, the proportion of particles moving at a given speed within this range is determined by probability as described by the Maxwell–Boltzmann distribution.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] 2* shows the speed distribution of 5500 K helium atoms.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] However, a certain proportion of atoms at any given instant are moving faster while others are moving relatively slowly; some are momentarily at a virtual standstill (off the *x*-axis to the right).
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] This graph uses *inverse speed* for its *x*-axis so the shape of the curve can easily be compared to the curves in *Fig.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] In both graphs, zero on the *x*-axis represents infinite temperature.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] Additionally, the *x*- and *y*-axes on both graphs are scaled proportionally.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] Although very specialized laboratory equipment is required to directly detect translational motions, the resultant collisions by atoms or molecules with small particles suspended in a fluid produces Brownian motion that can be seen with an ordinary microscope.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] The translational motions of elementary particles are *very* fast and temperatures close to absolute zero are required to directly observe them.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] For instance, when scientists at the NIST achieved a record-setting low temperature of 700 nK (billionths of a kelvin) in 1994, they used optical lattice laser equipment to adiabatically cool cesium atoms.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] They then turned off the entrapment lasers and directly measured atom velocities of 7 mm per second in order to calculate their temperature.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] Formulas for calculating the velocity and speed of translational motion are given in the following footnote.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] It is neither difficult to imagine atomic motions due to kinetic temperature, nor distinguish between such motions and those due to zero-point energy.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] Consider the following hypothetical thought experiment, as illustrated in *Fig.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] 2.5* at left, with an atom that is exceedingly close to absolute zero.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] Imagine peering through a common optical microscope set to 400 power, which is about the maximum practical magnification for optical microscopes.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] Such microscopes generally provide fields of view a bit over 0.4 mm in diameter.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] At the center of the field of view is a single levitated argon atom (argon comprises about 0.93% of air) that is illuminated and glowing against a dark backdrop.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] If this argon atom was at a beyond-record-setting *one-trillionth* of a kelvin above absolute zero, and was moving perpendicular to the field of view towards the right, it would require 13.9 seconds to move from the center of the image to the 200 μm tick mark.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] As the argon atom slowly moved, the positional jitter due to zero-point energy would be much less than the 200 nm (0.0002 mm) resolution of an optical microscope.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] Importantly, the atom's translational velocity of 14.43 μm/s constitutes all its retained kinetic energy due to not being precisely at absolute zero.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] Were the atom *precisely* at absolute zero, imperceptible jostling due to zero-point energy would cause it to very slightly wander, but the atom would perpetually be located, on average, at the same spot within the field of view.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] This is analogous to a boat that has had its motor turned off and is now bobbing slightly in relatively calm and windless ocean waters; even though the boat randomly drifts to and fro, it stays in the same spot in the long term and makes no headway through the water.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] Accordingly, an atom that was precisely at absolute zero would not be "motionless", and yet, a statistically significant collection of such atoms would have zero net kinetic energy available to transfer to any other collection of atoms.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] This is because regardless of the kinetic temperature of the second collection of atoms, they too experience the effects of zero-point energy.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] Such are the consequences of statistical mechanics and the nature of thermodynamics.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] As mentioned above, there are other ways molecules can jiggle besides the three translational degrees of freedom that imbue substances with their kinetic temperature.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] As can be seen in the animation at right, molecules are complex objects; they are a population of atoms and thermal agitation can strain their internal chemical bonds in three different ways: via rotation, bond length, and bond angle movements; these are all types of *internal degrees of freedom*.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] This makes molecules distinct from *monatomic* substances (consisting of individual atoms) like the noble gases helium and argon, which have only the three translational degrees of freedom (the *x*-, *y*-, and *z*-axes).
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] Kinetic energy is stored in molecules' internal degrees of freedom, which gives them an *internal temperature*.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] Even though these motions are called "internal", the external portions of molecules still move—rather like the jiggling of a stationary water balloon.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] This permits the two-way exchange of kinetic energy between internal motions and translational motions with each molecular collision.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] Accordingly, as internal energy is removed from molecules, both their kinetic temperature (the kinetic energy of translational motion) and their internal temperature simultaneously diminish in equal proportions.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] This phenomenon is described by the equipartition theorem, which states that for any bulk quantity of a substance in equilibrium, the kinetic energy of particle motion is evenly distributed among all the active degrees of freedom available to the particles.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] The kinetic energy stored internally in molecules causes substances to contain more heat energy at any given temperature and to absorb additional internal energy for a given temperature increase.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] This is because any kinetic energy that is, at a given instant, bound in internal motions, is not contributing to the molecules' translational motions at that same instant.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] This extra kinetic energy simply increases the amount of internal energy that substance absorbs for a given temperature rise.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] This property is known as a substance's specific heat capacity.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] Different molecules absorb different amounts of internal energy for each incremental increase in temperature; that is, they have different specific heat capacities.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] High specific heat capacity arises, in part, because certain substances' molecules possess more internal degrees of freedom than others do.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] For instance, room-temperature nitrogen, which is a diatomic molecule, has *five* active degrees of freedom: the three comprising translational motion plus two rotational degrees of freedom internally.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] Not surprisingly, in accordance with the equipartition theorem, nitrogen has five-thirds the specific heat capacity per mole (a specific number of molecules) as do the monatomic gases.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] Another example is gasoline (see table showing its specific heat capacity).
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] Gasoline can absorb a large amount of heat energy per mole with only a modest temperature change because each molecule comprises an average of 21 atoms and therefore has many internal degrees of freedom.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] Even larger, more complex molecules can have dozens of internal degrees of freedom.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] One particular heat conduction mechanism occurs when translational motion, the particle motion underlying temperature, transfers momentum from particle to particle in collisions.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] In gases, these translational motions are of the nature shown above in *Fig.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] As can be seen in that animation, not only does momentum (heat) diffuse throughout the volume of the gas through serial collisions, but entire molecules or atoms can move forward into new territory, bringing their kinetic energy with them.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] Consequently, temperature differences equalize throughout gases very quickly—especially for light atoms or molecules; convection speeds this process even more.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] Translational motion in *solids*, however, takes the form of *phonons* (see *Fig.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] Phonons are constrained, quantized wave packets that travel at the speed of sound of a given substance.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] The manner in which phonons interact within a solid determines a variety of its properties, including its thermal conductivity.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] In electrically insulating solids, phonon-based heat conduction is *usually* inefficient and such solids are considered *thermal insulators* (such as glass, plastic, rubber, ceramic, and rock).
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] This is because in solids, atoms and molecules are locked into place relative to their neighbors and are not free to roam.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] Metals however, are not restricted to only phonon-based heat conduction.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] Thermal energy conducts through metals extraordinarily quickly because instead of direct molecule-to-molecule collisions, the vast majority of thermal energy is mediated via very light, mobile *conduction electrons*.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] This is why there is a near-perfect correlation between metals' thermal conductivity and their electrical conductivity.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] Conduction electrons imbue metals with their extraordinary conductivity because they are *delocalized* (i.e., not tied to a specific atom) and behave rather like a sort of quantum gas due to the effects of *zero-point energy* (for more on ZPE, see *Note 1* below).
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] Furthermore, electrons are relatively light with a rest mass only 1⁄1836 that of a proton.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] However, a bullet accelerates faster than a rifle given an equal force.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] Since kinetic energy increases as the square of velocity, nearly all the kinetic energy goes into the bullet, not the rifle, even though both experience the same force from the expanding propellant gases.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] In the same manner, because they are much less massive, thermal energy is readily borne by mobile conduction electrons.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] Additionally, because they are delocalized and *very* fast, kinetic thermal energy conducts extremely quickly through metals with abundant conduction electrons.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] Thermal radiation is a byproduct of the collisions arising from various vibrational motions of atoms.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] These collisions cause the electrons of the atoms to emit thermal photons (known as black-body radiation).
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] Photons are emitted anytime an electric charge is accelerated (as happens when electron clouds of two atoms collide).
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] Even *individual molecules* with internal temperatures greater than absolute zero also emit black-body radiation from their atoms.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] In any bulk quantity of a substance at equilibrium, black-body photons are emitted across a range of wavelengths in a spectrum that has a bell curve-like shape called a Planck curve (see graph in *Fig.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] The top of a Planck curve (the peak emittance wavelength) is located in a particular part of the electromagnetic spectrum depending on the temperature of the black-body.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] Substances at extreme cryogenic temperatures emit at long radio wavelengths whereas extremely hot temperatures produce short gamma rays (see § Table of thermodynamic temperatures).
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] Black-body radiation diffuses thermal energy throughout a substance as the photons are absorbed by neighboring atoms, transferring momentum in the process.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] Black-body photons also easily escape from a substance and can be absorbed by the ambient environment; kinetic energy is lost in the process.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] As established by the Stefan–Boltzmann law, the intensity of black-body radiation increases as the fourth power of absolute temperature.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] Thus, a black-body at 824 K (just short of glowing dull red) emits 60 times the radiant power as it does at 296 K (room temperature).
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] This is why one can so easily feel the radiant heat from hot objects at a distance.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] At higher temperatures, such as those found in an incandescent lamp, black-body radiation can be the principal mechanism by which thermal energy escapes a system.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] The table below shows various points on the thermodynamic scale, in order of increasing temperature.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] For a true black body (which the plasma was not).
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] The Z machine's dominant emission originated from 40 MK electrons (soft x–ray emissions) within the plasma.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] The kinetic energy of particle motion is just one contributor to the total thermal energy in a substance; another is *phase transitions*, which are the potential energy of molecular bonds that can form in a substance as it cools (such as during condensing and freezing).
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] The thermal energy required for a phase transition is called *latent heat*.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] This phenomenon may more easily be grasped by considering it in the reverse direction: latent heat is the energy required to *break* chemical bonds (such as during evaporation and melting).
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] Almost everyone is familiar with the effects of phase transitions; for instance, steam at 100 °C can cause severe burns much faster than the 100 °C air from a hair dryer.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] This occurs because a large amount of latent heat is liberated as steam condenses into liquid water on the skin.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] Even though thermal energy is liberated or absorbed during phase transitions, pure chemical elements, compounds, and eutectic alloys exhibit no temperature change whatsoever while they undergo them (see *Fig.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] Consider one particular type of phase transition: melting.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] When a solid is melting, crystal lattice chemical bonds are being broken apart; the substance is transitioning from what is known as a *more ordered state* to a *less ordered state*.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] 7*, the melting of ice is shown within the lower left box heading from blue to green.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] At one specific thermodynamic point, the melting point (which is 0 °C across a wide pressure range in the case of water), all the atoms or molecules are, on average, at the maximum energy threshold their chemical bonds can withstand without breaking away from the lattice.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] Chemical bonds are all-or-nothing forces: they either hold fast, or break; there is no in-between state.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] The effect is rather like popcorn: at a certain temperature, additional thermal energy cannot make the kernels any hotter until the transition (popping) is complete.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] If the process is reversed (as in the freezing of a liquid), thermal energy must be removed from a substance.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] As stated above, the thermal energy required for a phase transition is called *latent heat*.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] In the specific cases of melting and freezing, it is called *enthalpy of fusion* or *heat of fusion*.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] If the molecular bonds in a crystal lattice are strong, the heat of fusion can be relatively great, typically in the range of 6 to 30 kJ per mole for water and most of the metallic elements.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] If the substance is one of the monatomic gases (which have little tendency to form molecular bonds) the heat of fusion is more modest, ranging from 0.021 to 2.3 kJ per mole.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] Relatively speaking, phase transitions can be truly energetic events.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] To completely melt ice at 0 °C into water at 0 °C, one must add roughly 80 times the thermal energy as is required to increase the temperature of the same mass of liquid water by one degree Celsius.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] The metals' ratios are even greater, typically in the range of 400 to 1200 times.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] The phase transition of boiling is much more energetic than freezing.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] For instance, the energy required to completely boil or vaporize water (what is known as *enthalpy of vaporization*) is roughly 540 times that required for a one-degree increase.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] Water's sizable enthalpy of vaporization is why one's skin can be burned so quickly as steam condenses on it (heading from red to green in *Fig.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] 7* above); water vapors (gas phase) are liquefied on the skin with releasing a large amount of energy (enthalpy) to the environment including the skin, resulting in skin damage.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] Water's highly energetic enthalpy of vaporization is also an important factor underlying why *solar pool covers* (floating, insulated blankets that cover swimming pools when the pools are not in use) are so effective at reducing heating costs: they prevent evaporation.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] (In other words, taking energy from water when it is evaporated is limited.) For instance, the evaporation of just 20 mm of water from a 1.29 m-deep pool chills its water 8.4 °C (15.1 °F).
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] The total energy of all translational and internal particle motions, including that of conduction electrons, plus the potential energy of phase changes, plus zero-point energy of a substance comprise the *internal energy* of it.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] When particles of a substance are as close as possible to complete rest and retain only ZPE (zero-point energy)-induced quantum mechanical motion, the substance is at the temperature of absolute zero (T = 0).
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] Often, all the phase changes that *can* occur in a substance, *will* have occurred by the time it reaches absolute zero.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] Notably, T = 0 helium remains liquid at room pressure (*Fig.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] 9* at right) and must be under a pressure of at least 25 bar (2.5 MPa) to crystallize.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] This is because helium's heat of fusion (the energy required to melt helium ice) is so low (only 21 joules per mole) that the motion-inducing effect of zero-point energy is sufficient to prevent it from freezing at lower pressures.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] A further complication is that many solids change their crystal structure to more compact arrangements at extremely high pressures (up to millions of bars, or hundreds of gigapascals).
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] These are known as *solid–solid phase transitions* wherein latent heat is liberated as a crystal lattice changes to a more thermodynamically favorable, compact one.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] The above complexities make for rather cumbersome blanket statements regarding the internal energy in T = 0 substances.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] Regardless of pressure though, what *can* be said is that at absolute zero, all solids with a lowest-energy crystal lattice such those with a *closest-packed arrangement* (see *Fig.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] 8*, above left) contain minimal internal energy, retaining only that due to the ever-present background of zero-point energy.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] One can also say that for a given substance at constant pressure, absolute zero is the point of lowest *enthalpy* (a measure of work potential that takes internal energy, pressure, and volume into consideration).
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] Lastly, all T = 0 substances contain zero kinetic thermal energy.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] Thermodynamic temperature is useful not only for scientists, it can also be useful for lay-people in many disciplines involving gases.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] By expressing variables in absolute terms and applying Gay-Lussac's law of temperature/pressure proportionality, solutions to everyday problems are straightforward; for instance, calculating how a temperature change affects the pressure inside an automobile tire.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] If the tire has a cold gage pressure of 200 kPa, then its absolute pressure is 300 kPa.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] Room temperature ("cold" in tire terms) is 296 K.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] If the tire temperature is 20 °C hotter (20 kelvins), the solution is calculated as ⁠316 K/296 K⁠ = 6.8% greater thermodynamic temperature *and* absolute pressure; that is, an absolute pressure of 320 kPa, which is a gage pressure of 220 kPa.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] The thermodynamic temperature is closely linked to the ideal gas law and its consequences.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] It can be linked also to the second law of thermodynamics.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] The thermodynamic temperature can be shown to have special properties, and in particular can be seen to be uniquely defined (up to some constant multiplicative factor) by considering the efficiency of idealized heat engines.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] Thus the ratio *T*2/*T*1 of two temperatures *T*1 and *T*2 is the same in all absolute scales.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] Strictly speaking, the temperature of a system is well-defined only if it is at thermal equilibrium.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] From a microscopic viewpoint, a material is at thermal equilibrium if the quantity of heat between its individual particles cancel out.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] There are many possible scales of temperature, derived from a variety of observations of physical phenomena.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] Loosely stated, temperature differences dictate the direction of heat between two systems such that their combined energy is maximally distributed among their lowest possible states.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] To better understand the relationship between temperature and entropy, consider the relationship between heat, work and temperature illustrated in the Carnot heat engine.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] The engine converts heat into work by directing a temperature gradient between a higher temperature heat source, *T*H, and a lower temperature heat sink, *T*C, through a gas filled piston.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] The work done per cycle is equal in magnitude to net heat taken up, which is sum of the heat *q*H taken up by the engine from the high-temperature source, plus the waste heat given off by the engine, *q*C < 0.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] Thus the efficiency depends only on |*q*C| / |*q*H|.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] Carnot's theorem states that all reversible engines operating between the same heat reservoirs are equally efficient.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] In addition, a reversible heat engine operating between a pair of thermal reservoirs at temperatures *T*1 and *T*3 must have the same efficiency as one consisting of two cycles, one between *T*1 and another (intermediate) temperature *T*2, and the second between *T*2 and *T*3.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] Here, the engine 1 is the one cycle engine, and the engines 2 and 3 make the two cycle engine where there is the intermediate reservoir at *T*2.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] We also have used the fact that the heat $q_{2}$ passes through the intermediate thermal reservoir at $T_{2}$ without losing its energy.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] In order to have the consistency in the last equation, the heat $q_{2}$ flown from the engine 2 to the intermediate reservoir must be equal to the heat $q_{2}^{*}$ flown out from the reservoir to the engine 3.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] But since the first function is *not* a function of *T*2, the product of the final two functions *must* result in the removal of *T*2 as a variable.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] I.e. the ratio of heat exchanged is a function of the respective temperatures at which they occur.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] We can choose any monotonic function for our $g(T)$ ; it is a matter of convenience and convention that we choose $g(T)=T$ .
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] Choosing then *one* fixed reference temperature (i.e. triple point of water), we establish the thermodynamic temperature scale.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] Note that for *T*C = 0 the efficiency is 100% and that efficiency becomes greater than 100% for *T*C < 0, which is unrealistic.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p01] The function S is the entropy of the system, mentioned previously, and the change of S around any cycle is zero (as is necessary for any state function).
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p02] Guillaume Amontons (1663–1705) published two papers in 1702 and 1703 that may be used to credit him as being the first researcher to deduce the existence of a fundamental (thermodynamic) temperature scale featuring an absolute zero.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p02] He made the discovery while endeavoring to improve upon the air thermometers in use at the time.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p02] His J-tube thermometers comprised a mercury column that was supported by a fixed mass of air entrapped within the sensing portion of the thermometer.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p02] In thermodynamic terms, his thermometers relied upon the volume / temperature relationship of gas under constant pressure.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p02] His measurements of the boiling point of water and the melting point of ice showed that regardless of the mass of air trapped inside his thermometers or the weight of mercury the air was supporting, the reduction in air volume at the ice point was always the same ratio.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p02] This observation led him to posit that a sufficient reduction in temperature would reduce the air volume to zero.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p02] In fact, his calculations projected that absolute zero was equivalent to −240 °C—only 33.15 degrees short of the true value of −273.15 °C.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p02] Amonton's discovery of a one-to-one relationship between absolute temperature and absolute pressure was rediscovered a century later and popularized within the scientific community by Joseph Louis Gay-Lussac.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p02] Today, this principle of thermodynamics is commonly known as *Gay-Lussac's law* but is also known as *Amonton's law*.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p02] In 1742, Anders Celsius (1701–1744) created a "backwards" version of the modern Celsius temperature scale.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p02] In Celsius's original scale, zero represented the boiling point of water and 100 represented the melting point of ice.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p02] In his paper *Observations of two persistent degrees on a thermometer*, he recounted his experiments showing that ice's melting point was effectively unaffected by pressure.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p02] He also determined with remarkable precision how water's boiling point varied as a function of atmospheric pressure.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p02] He proposed that zero on his temperature scale (water's boiling point) would be calibrated at the mean barometric pressure at mean sea level.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p02] Coincident with the death of Anders Celsius in 1744, the botanist Carl Linnaeus (1707–1778) effectively reversed Celsius's scale upon receipt of his first thermometer featuring a scale where zero represented the melting point of ice and 100 represented water's boiling point.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p02] The custom-made *Linnaeus-thermometer*, for use in his greenhouses, was made by Daniel Ekström, Sweden's leading maker of scientific instruments at the time.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p02] For the next 204 years, the scientific and thermometry communities worldwide referred to this scale as the *centigrade scale*.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p02] Temperatures on the centigrade scale were often reported simply as *degrees* or, when greater specificity was desired, *degrees centigrade*.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p02] The symbol for temperature values on this scale was °C (in several formats over the years).
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p02] The 9th CGPM (General Conference on Weights and Measures and the CIPM (International Committee for Weights and Measures formally adopted *degree Celsius* (symbol: °C) in 1948.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p02] In his book *Pyrometrie* (1777) completed four months before his death, Johann Heinrich Lambert (1728–1777), sometimes incorrectly referred to as Joseph Lambert, proposed an absolute temperature scale based on the pressure/temperature relationship of a fixed volume of gas.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p02] This is distinct from the volume/temperature relationship of gas under constant pressure that Guillaume Amontons discovered 75 years earlier.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p02] Lambert stated that absolute zero was the point where a simple straight-line extrapolation reached zero gas pressure and was equal to −270 °C.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p02] Notwithstanding the work of Guillaume Amontons 85 years earlier, Jacques Alexandre César Charles (1746–1823) is often credited with discovering (circa 1787), but not publishing, that the volume of a gas under constant pressure is proportional to its absolute temperature.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p02] Joseph Louis Gay-Lussac (1778–1850) published work in 1802 (acknowledging the unpublished lab notes of Jacques Charles fifteen years earlier) describing how the volume of gas under constant pressure changes linearly with its absolute (thermodynamic) temperature.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p02] This behavior is called Charles's law and is one of the gas laws.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p02] His are the first known formulas to use the number 273 for the expansion coefficient of gas relative to the melting point of ice (indicating that absolute zero was equivalent to −273 °C).
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p02] William Thomson (1824–1907), also known as Lord Kelvin, wrote in his 1848 paper "On an Absolute Thermometric Scale" of the need for a scale whereby *infinite cold* (absolute zero) was the scale's zero point, and which used the degree Celsius for its unit increment.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p02] Like Gay-Lussac, Thomson calculated that absolute zero was equivalent to −273 °C on the air thermometers of the time.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p02] This absolute scale is known today as the Kelvin thermodynamic temperature scale.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p02] Thomson's value of −273 was derived from 0.00366, which was the accepted expansion coefficient of gas per degree Celsius relative to the ice point.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p02] The inverse of −0.00366 expressed to five significant digits is −273.22 °C which is remarkably close to the true value of −273.15 °C.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p02] In the paper he proposed to define temperature using idealized heat engines.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p02] Note that like Carnot, Kelvin worked under the assumption that heat is conserved ("the conversion of heat (or caloric) into mechanical effect is probably impossible"), and if heat Q goes into the heat engine, then heat Q must come out.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p02] Kelvin, realizing after Joule's experiments that heat is not a conserved quantity but is convertible with mechanical work, modified his scale in the 1851 work *An Account of Carnot's Theory of the Motive Power of Heat*.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p02] The above definition fixes the ratios between absolute temperatures, but it does not fix a scale for absolute temperature.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p02] For the scale, Thomson proposed to use the Celsius degree, that is, ${\frac {1}{100}}$ the interval between the freezing and the boiling point of water.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p02] In 1859 Macquorn Rankine (1820–1872) proposed a thermodynamic temperature scale similar to William Thomson's but which used the degree Fahrenheit for its unit increment, that is, ${\frac {1}{180}}$ the interval between the freezing and the boiling point of water.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p02] This absolute scale is known today as the Rankine thermodynamic temperature scale.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p02] Ludwig Boltzmann (1844–1906) made major contributions to thermodynamics between 1877 and 1884 through an understanding of the role that particle kinetics and black body radiation played.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p02] His name is now attached to several of the formulas used today in thermodynamics.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p02] Gas thermometry experiments carefully calibrated to the melting point of ice and boiling point of water showed in the 1930s that absolute zero was equivalent to −273.15 °C.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p02] Resolution 3 of the 9th General Conference on Weights and Measures (CGPM) in 1948 fixed the triple point of water at precisely 0.01 °C.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p02] At this time, the triple point still had no formal definition for its equivalent kelvin value, which the resolution declared "will be fixed at a later date".
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p02] The implication is that if the value of absolute zero measured in the 1930s was truly −273.15 °C, then the triple point of water (0.01 °C) was equivalent to 273.16 K.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p02] Additionally, both the International Committee for Weights and Measures (CIPM) and the CGPM formally adopted the name *Celsius* for the *degree Celsius* and the *Celsius temperature scale*.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p02] This, in combination with Resolution 3 of the 9th CGPM, had the effect of defining absolute zero as being precisely zero kelvins and −273.15 °C.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p02] Resolution 3 of the 13th CGPM in 1967/1968 renamed the unit increment of thermodynamic temperature *kelvin*, symbol K, replacing *degree absolute*, symbol °K.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p02] Further, feeling it useful to more explicitly define the magnitude of the unit increment, the 13th CGPM also decided in Resolution 4 that "The kelvin, unit of thermodynamic temperature, is the fraction 1/273.16 of the thermodynamic temperature of the triple point of water".
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p02] In November 2018, the 26th General Conference on Weights and Measures (CGPM) changed the definition of the Kelvin by fixing the Boltzmann constant to 1.380649×10−23 when expressed in the unit J/K.
[src:carnot-cycle/absolute-temperature-p02] This change (and other changes in the definition of SI units) was made effective on the 144th anniversary of the Metre Convention, 20 May 2019.
[src:carnot-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] An **absorption refrigerator** is a refrigerator that uses a heat source to provide the energy needed to drive the cooling process.
[src:carnot-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] Solar energy, burning a fossil fuel, waste heat from factories, and district heating systems are examples of heat sources that can be used.
[src:carnot-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] An absorption refrigerator uses two coolants, the first coolant performing evaporative cooling before being absorbed into the second coolant.
[src:carnot-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] Heat is then needed to reset the two coolants to their initial states.
[src:carnot-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] Absorption refrigerators are commonly used in recreational vehicles (RVs), campers, and caravans because the heat required to power them can be provided by either a propane fuel burner, a low-voltage DC electric heater (from a battery or vehicle electrical system) or a mains-powered electric heater.
[src:carnot-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] Absorption refrigerators can also be used to air-condition buildings using the waste heat from a gas turbine or water heater in the building.
[src:carnot-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] Using waste heat from a gas turbine makes the turbine very efficient because it first produces electricity, then hot water, and finally, air-conditioning—trigeneration.
[src:carnot-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] Unlike more common vapor-compression refrigeration systems, an absorption refrigerator has no moving parts.
[src:carnot-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] Absorption refrigerators are an alternative to compressor refrigerators where electricity is unreliable, costly, or unavailable; where noise from the compressor is problematic; or where surplus heat is available.
[src:carnot-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] In 1748 in Glasgow, William Cullen invented the basis for modern refrigeration, although he is not credited with a usable application.
[src:carnot-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] More on history of refrigeration can be found in the paragraph Refrigeration Research on page Refrigeration.
[src:carnot-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] Absorption refrigeration uses the same principle as adsorption refrigeration, which was invented by Michael Faraday in 1821.
[src:carnot-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] Instead of using a solid adsorber, an absorber in an absorption system absorbs the refrigerant vapour into a liquid.
[src:carnot-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] Absorption cooling was invented by the French scientist Ferdinand Carré in 1858.
[src:carnot-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] The original design used water and sulphuric acid.
[src:carnot-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] The principle was enhanced with a three-fluid configuration in 1922 by Baltzar von Platen and Carl Munters, two students at the Royal Institute of Technology in Stockholm.
[src:carnot-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] This "Platen-Munters" design can operate without a pump.
[src:carnot-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] Commercial production began in 1923 by the newly-formed company *AB Arctic*, which was bought by Electrolux in 1925.
[src:carnot-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] In the 1960s, absorption refrigeration saw a renaissance due to the substantial demand for refrigerators for caravans.
[src:carnot-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] AB Electrolux later established a subsidiary in the United States, named Dometic Sales Corporation.
[src:carnot-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] The company marketed refrigerators for recreational vehicles (RVs) under the *Dometic* brand.
[src:carnot-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] In 2001, Electrolux sold most of its leisure products line to the venture-capital company EQT which created *Dometic* as a stand-alone company.
[src:carnot-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] Dometic still sold absorption fridges as of July 2025.
[src:carnot-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] In 1926, Albert Einstein and his former student Leó Szilárd proposed an alternative design known as the Einstein refrigerator.
[src:carnot-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] At the 2007 TED Conference, Adam Grosser presented his research of an "intermittent absorption" vaccine refrigeration unit for use in third world countries.
[src:carnot-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] The refrigerator is a small unit placed over a campfire, that can later be used to cool 15 litres (3.3 imp gal; 4.0 US gal) of water to just above freezing for 24 hours in a 30 °C (86 °F) environment.
[src:carnot-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] The concept was similar to an early refrigeration device known as an Icyball.
[src:carnot-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] Common absorption refrigerators use a refrigerant with a very low boiling point (less than −18 °C (0 °F)) just like compressor refrigerators.
[src:carnot-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] Compression refrigerators typically use an HCFC or HFC, while absorption refrigerators typically use ammonia or water and need at least a second fluid able to absorb the coolant, the *absorbent*, respectively water (for ammonia) or brine (for water).
[src:carnot-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] Both types use evaporative cooling: when the refrigerant evaporates (boils), it takes some heat away with it, providing the cooling effect.
[src:carnot-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] The main difference between the two systems is the way the refrigerant is changed from a gas back into a liquid so that the cycle can repeat.
[src:carnot-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] An absorption refrigerator changes the gas back into a liquid using a method that needs only heat, and has no moving parts other than the fluids.
[src:carnot-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] The system thus silently provides for the mechanical circulation of the liquid without a usual pump.
[src:carnot-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] A third fluid, gaseous, is usually added to avoid pressure concerns when condensation occurs (see below).
[src:carnot-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] In comparison, a compressor based heat pump works by pumping refrigerant gas from an evaporator to a condenser.
[src:carnot-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] This reduces the pressure and boiling temperature in the evaporator and increases the pressure and condensing temperature in the condenser.
[src:carnot-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] Energy from an electric motor or internal combustion engine is required to operate the compressor pump.
[src:carnot-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] Compressing the refrigerant uses this energy to do work on the gas, increasing its temperature.
[src:carnot-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] The warm, high pressure gas then enters the condenser where it undergoes a phase change to a liquid and releases heat to the condenser's surroundings.
[src:carnot-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] Warm liquid refrigerant moves from the high pressure condenser to the low pressure evaporator via an expansion valve, also known as a throttling valve or a Joule-Thomson valve.
[src:carnot-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] The expansion valve partially vaporizes the refrigerant cooling it via evaporative cooling, and the resulting vapor is cooled via expansive cooling.
[src:carnot-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] This is a combination of Joule-Thomson cooling and work done by the expanding gas, both at the expense of the internal energy of the gas.
[src:carnot-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] The cold, low pressure liquid refrigerant will now absorb heat from the evaporator's surroundings and vaporize.
[src:carnot-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] The resulting gas enters the compressor, and the cycle begins again.
[src:carnot-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] A simple absorption refrigeration system common in large commercial plants uses a solution of lithium bromide or lithium chloride salt and water.
[src:carnot-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] Water under low pressure is evaporated from the coils that are to be chilled.
[src:carnot-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] The water is absorbed by a lithium bromide/water solution.
[src:carnot-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] The system drives the water out of the lithium bromide solution with heat.
[src:carnot-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] Another variant uses air, water, and a salt water solution.
[src:carnot-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] The intake of warm, moist air is passed through a sprayed solution of salt water.
[src:carnot-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] The spray lowers the humidity but does not significantly change the temperature.
[src:carnot-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] The less humid, warm air is then passed through an evaporative cooler, consisting of a spray of fresh water, which cools and re-humidifies the air.
[src:carnot-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] Humidity is removed from the cooled air with another spray of salt solution, providing the outlet of cool, dry air.
[src:carnot-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] The salt solution is regenerated by heating it under low pressure, causing water to evaporate.
[src:carnot-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] The water evaporated from the salt solution is re-condensed, and rerouted back to the evaporative cooler.
[src:carnot-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] A single-pressure absorption refrigerator takes advantage of the fact that a liquid's evaporation rate depends upon the *partial* pressure of the vapor above the liquid and goes up with lower partial pressure.
[src:carnot-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] The refrigerator uses three substances: ammonia, hydrogen gas, and water.
[src:carnot-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] The cycle is closed, with all hydrogen, water and ammonia collected and endlessly reused.
[src:carnot-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] The cooling cycle starts with liquid ammonia at room temperature entering the evaporator.
[src:carnot-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] The volume of the evaporator is greater than the volume of the liquid, with the excess space occupied by a mixture of gaseous ammonia and hydrogen.
[src:carnot-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] The presence of hydrogen lowers the partial pressure of the ammonia gas, thus lowering the evaporation point of the liquid below the temperature of the refrigerator's interior.
[src:carnot-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] Ammonia evaporates, taking a small amount of heat from the liquid and lowering the liquid's temperature.
[src:carnot-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] It continues to evaporate, while the large enthalpy of vaporization (heat) flows from the warmer refrigerator interior to the cooler liquid ammonia and then to more ammonia gas.
[src:carnot-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] In the next two steps, the ammonia gas is separated from the hydrogen so it can be reused.
[src:carnot-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] The next step separates the ammonia and water.
[src:carnot-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] The ammonia/water solution flows to the generator (boiler), where heat is applied to boil off the ammonia, leaving most of the water (which has a higher boiling point) behind.
[src:carnot-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] Some water vapor and bubbles remain mixed with the ammonia; this water is removed in the final separation step, by passing it through the separator, an uphill series of twisted pipes with minor obstacles to pop the bubbles, allowing the water vapor to condense and drain back to the generator.
[src:carnot-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] The pure ammonia gas then enters the condenser.
[src:carnot-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] In this heat exchanger, the hot ammonia gas transfers its heat to the outside air, which is below the boiling point of the full-pressure ammonia, and therefore condenses.
[src:carnot-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] The condensed (liquid) ammonia flows down to be mixed with the hydrogen gas released from the absorption step, repeating the cycle.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] An **adiabatic process** (*adiabatic* from Ancient Greek ἀδιάβατος*(*adiábatos*)* 'impassable') is a type of thermodynamic process whereby a transfer of energy between the thermodynamic system and its environment is accompanied neither by a transfer of entropy nor of amounts of constituents.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] Unlike an isothermal process, an adiabatic process transfers energy to the surroundings only as work and/or mass flow.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] As a key concept in thermodynamics, the adiabatic process supports the theory that explains the first law of thermodynamics.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] The opposite term to "adiabatic" is *diabatic*.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] Some chemical and physical processes occur too rapidly for energy to enter or leave the system as heat, allowing a convenient "adiabatic approximation".
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] For example, the adiabatic flame temperature uses this approximation to calculate the upper limit of flame temperature by assuming combustion loses no heat to its surroundings.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] In meteorology, adiabatic expansion and cooling of moist air, which can be triggered by winds flowing up and over a mountain for example, can cause the water vapor pressure to exceed the saturation vapor pressure.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] Expansion and cooling beyond the saturation vapor pressure is often idealized as a *pseudo-adiabatic process* whereby excess vapor instantly precipitates into water droplets.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] The change in temperature of air undergoing pseudo-adiabatic expansion differs from air undergoing adiabatic expansion because latent heat is released by precipitation.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] A process without transfer of thermal energy (heat) to or from a system, so that *Q* = 0, is called adiabatic, and such a system is said to be adiabatically isolated.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] The simplifying assumption frequently made is that a process is adiabatic.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] For example, the compression of a gas within a cylinder of an engine is assumed to occur so rapidly that on the time scale of the compression process, little of the system's energy can be transferred out as heat to the surroundings.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] Even though the cylinders are not insulated and are quite conductive, that process is idealized to be adiabatic.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] The same can be said to be true for the expansion process of such a system.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] The assumption of adiabatic isolation is useful and often combined with other such idealizations to calculate a good first approximation of a system's behaviour.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] For example, according to Laplace, when sound travels in a gas, there is no time for heat conduction in the medium, and so the propagation of sound is adiabatic.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] For such an adiabatic process, the modulus of elasticity (Young's modulus) can be expressed as *E* = *γP*, where γ is the ratio of specific heats at constant pressure and at constant volume ( *γ* = ⁠*Cp*/*Cv*⁠) and *P* is the pressure of the gas.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] For a closed system, one may write the first law of thermodynamics as Δ*U* = *Q* − *W*, where Δ*U* denotes the change of the system's internal energy, Q the quantity of energy added to it as heat, and W the work done by the system on its surroundings.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] Naturally occurring adiabatic processes are irreversible (entropy is produced).
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] The transfer of energy as work into an adiabatically isolated system can be imagined as being of two idealized extreme kinds.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] In one such kind, no entropy is produced within the system (no friction, viscous dissipation, etc.), and the work is only pressure-volume work (denoted by *P* d*V*).
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] In nature, this ideal kind occurs only approximately because it demands an infinitely slow process and no sources of dissipation.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] The other extreme kind of work is isochoric work (d*V* = 0), for which energy is added as work solely through friction or viscous dissipation within the system.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] A stirrer that transfers energy to a viscous fluid of an adiabatically isolated system with rigid walls, without phase change, will cause a rise in temperature of the fluid, but that work is not recoverable.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] The second law of thermodynamics observes that a natural process, of transfer of energy as work, always consists at least of isochoric work and often both of these extreme kinds of work.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] Every natural process, adiabatic or not, is irreversible, with Δ*S* > 0, as friction or viscosity are always present to some extent.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] The adiabatic compression of a gas causes a rise in temperature of the gas.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] Adiabatic expansion against pressure, or a spring, causes a drop in temperature.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] In contrast, free expansion is an isothermal process for an ideal gas.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] This finds practical application in diesel engines which rely on the lack of heat dissipation during the compression stroke to elevate the fuel vapor temperature sufficiently to ignite it.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] Adiabatic compression occurs in the Earth's atmosphere when an air mass descends, for example, in a Katabatic wind, Foehn wind, or Chinook wind flowing downhill over a mountain range.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] When a parcel of air descends, the pressure on the parcel increases.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] Because of this increase in pressure, the parcel's volume decreases and its temperature increases as work is done on the parcel of air, thus increasing its internal energy, which manifests itself by a rise in the temperature of that mass of air.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] The parcel of air can only slowly dissipate the energy by conduction or radiation (heat), and to a first approximation it can be considered adiabatically isolated and the process an adiabatic process.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] Adiabatic expansion occurs when the pressure on an adiabatically isolated system is decreased, allowing it to expand in size, thus causing it to do work on its surroundings.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] When the pressure applied on a parcel of gas is reduced, the gas in the parcel is allowed to expand; as the volume increases, the temperature falls as its internal energy decreases.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] Adiabatic expansion occurs in the Earth's atmosphere with orographic lifting and lee waves, and this can form pilei or lenticular clouds.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] Due in part to adiabatic expansion in mountainous areas, snowfall actually occurs in some parts of the Sahara desert.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] Adiabatic expansion does not have to involve a fluid.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] One technique used to reach very low temperatures (thousandths and even millionths of a degree above absolute zero) is via adiabatic demagnetisation, where the change in magnetic field on a magnetic material is used to provide adiabatic expansion.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] Also, the contents of an expanding universe can be described (to first order) as an adiabatically expanding fluid.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] Rising magma also undergoes adiabatic expansion before eruption, particularly significant in the case of magmas that rise quickly from great depths such as kimberlites.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] In the Earth's convecting mantle (the asthenosphere) beneath the lithosphere, the mantle temperature is approximately an adiabat.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] The slight decrease in temperature with shallowing depth is due to the decrease in pressure the shallower the material is in the Earth.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] Such temperature changes can be quantified using the ideal gas law, or the hydrostatic equation for atmospheric processes.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] In practice, no process is truly adiabatic.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] Many processes rely on a large difference in time scales of the process of interest and the rate of heat dissipation across a system boundary, and thus are approximated by using an adiabatic assumption.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] There is always some heat loss, as no perfect insulators exist.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] Here CP is the specific heat for constant pressure, CV is the specific heat for constant volume, and f is the number of degrees of freedom (3 for a monatomic gas, 5 for a diatomic gas or a gas of linear molecules such as carbon dioxide).
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] For a monatomic ideal gas, *γ* = ⁠5/3⁠, and for a diatomic gas (such as nitrogen and oxygen, the main components of air), *γ* = ⁠7/5⁠.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] Note that the above formula is only applicable to classical ideal gases (that is, gases far above absolute zero temperature) and not Bose–Einstein or Fermi gases.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] where T is the absolute or thermodynamic temperature.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] The compression stroke in a gasoline engine can be used as an example of adiabatic compression.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] so the adiabatic constant for this example is about 6.31 Pa·m4.2 .
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] The gas is now compressed to a 0.1 L (0.0001 m3) volume, which we assume happens quickly enough that no heat enters or leaves the gas through the walls.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] We can solve for the temperature of the compressed gas in the engine cylinder as well, using the ideal gas law, P V = n R T (n is amount of gas in moles and R the gas constant for that gas).
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] That is a final temperature of 753 K, or 479 °C, or 896 °F, well above the ignition point of many fuels.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] A diesel engine operates under even more extreme conditions, with compression ratios of 16:1 or more being typical, in order to provide a very high gas pressure, which ensures immediate ignition of the injected fuel.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] For an adiabatic free expansion of an ideal gas, the gas is contained in an insulated container and then allowed to expand in a vacuum.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] Because there is no external pressure for the gas to expand against, the work done by or on the system is zero.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] Since this process does not involve any heat transfer or work, the first law of thermodynamics then implies that the net internal energy change of the system is zero.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] For an ideal gas, the temperature remains constant because the internal energy only depends on temperature in that case.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] Since at constant temperature, the entropy is proportional to the volume, the entropy increases in this case, therefore this process is irreversible.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] The definition of an adiabatic process is that heat transfer to the system is zero, *δQ* = 0.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] where d*U* is the change in the internal energy of the system and *δW* is work done *by* the system.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] Any work (*δW*) done must be done at the expense of internal energy U, since no heat δQ is being supplied from the surroundings.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] However, P does not remain constant during an adiabatic process but instead changes along with V.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] It is desired to know how the values of d*P* and d*V* relate to each other as the adiabatic process proceeds.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] where α is the number of degrees of freedom divided by 2, R is the universal gas constant and n is the number of moles in the system (a constant).
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] Equation (a4) is often expressed as d*U* = *n CV*d*T* because *CV* = *α R* .
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] An adiabat is a curve of constant entropy in a diagram.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] Some properties of adiabats on a *P* – *V* diagram are indicated.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] These properties may be read from the classical behaviour of ideal gases, except in the region where P V becomes small (low temperature), where quantum effects become important.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] Each adiabat intersects each isotherm exactly once.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] An adiabat looks similar to an isotherm, except that during an expansion, an adiabat loses more pressure than an isotherm, so it has a steeper inclination (more vertical).
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] If isotherms are concave towards the north-east direction (45° from V axis), then adiabats are concave towards the east north-east (31° from V axisaxis).
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] If adiabats and isotherms are graphed at regular intervals of entropy and temperature, respectively (like altitude on a contour map), then as the eye moves towards the axes (towards the south-west), it sees the density of isotherms stay constant, but it sees the density of adiabats grow.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] The exception is very near absolute zero, where the density of adiabats drops sharply and they become rare (see Nernst's theorem).
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] The term *adiabatic* (/ˌædiəˈbætɪk/) is an anglicization of the Greek term ἀδιάβατος "impassable" (used by Xenophon of rivers).
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] It is used in the thermodynamic sense by Rankine (1866), and adopted by Maxwell in 1871 (explicitly attributing the term to Rankine).
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] The etymological origin corresponds here to an impossibility of transfer of energy as heat and of transfer of matter across the wall.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] The Greek word ἀδιάβατος is formed from privative ἀ- ("not") and διαβατός, "passable", in turn deriving from διά ("through"), and βαῖνειν ("to walk, go, come").
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] Furthermore, in atmospheric thermodynamics, a diabatic process is one in which heat is exchanged.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] An adiabatic process is the opposite – a process in which no heat is exchanged.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] The adiabatic process has been important for thermodynamics since its early days.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] It was important in the work of Joule because it provided a way of nearly directly relating quantities of heat and work.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] Energy can enter or leave a thermodynamic system enclosed by walls that prevent mass transfer only as heat or work.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] Therefore, a quantity of work in such a system can be related almost directly to an equivalent quantity of heat in a cycle of two limbs.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] The first limb is an isochoric adiabatic work process increasing the system's internal energy; the second, an isochoric and workless heat transfer returning the system to its original state.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] Accordingly, Rankine measured quantity of heat in units of work, rather than as a calorimetric quantity.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] In 1854, Rankine used a quantity that he called "the thermodynamic function" that later was called entropy, and at that time he wrote also of the "curve of no transmission of heat", which he later called an adiabatic curve.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] Besides its two isothermal limbs, Carnot's cycle has two adiabatic limbs.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] For the foundations of thermodynamics, the conceptual importance of this was emphasized by Bryan, by Carathéodory, and by Born.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] The reason is that calorimetry presupposes a type of temperature as already defined before the statement of the first law of thermodynamics, such as one based on empirical scales.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] Such a presupposition involves making the distinction between empirical temperature and absolute temperature.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] Rather, the definition of absolute thermodynamic temperature is best left till the second law is available as a conceptual basis.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] In the eighteenth century, the law of conservation of energy was not yet fully formulated or established, and the nature of heat was debated.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] One approach to these problems was to regard heat, measured by calorimetry, as a primary substance that is conserved in quantity.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] By the middle of the nineteenth century, it was recognized as a form of energy, and the law of conservation of energy was thereby also recognized.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] The view that eventually established itself, and is currently regarded as right, is that the law of conservation of energy is a primary axiom, and that heat is to be analyzed as consequential.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] In this light, heat cannot be a component of the total energy of a single body because it is not a state variable but, rather, a variable that describes a transfer between two bodies.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] The adiabatic process is important because it is a logical ingredient of this current view.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] This present article is written from the viewpoint of macroscopic thermodynamics, and the word *adiabatic* is used in this article in the traditional way of thermodynamics, introduced by Rankine.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] It is pointed out in the present article that, for example, if a compression of a gas is rapid, then there is little time for heat transfer to occur, even when the gas is not adiabatically isolated by a definite wall.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] In this sense, a rapid compression of a gas is sometimes approximately or loosely said to be *adiabatic*, though often far from isentropic, even when the gas is not adiabatically isolated by a definite wall.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] Some authors, like Pippard, recommend using "adiathermal" to refer to processes where no heat-exchange occurs (such as Joule expansion), and "adiabatic" to reversible quasi-static adiathermal processes (so that rapid compression of a gas is *not* "adiabatic").
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] And Laidler has summarized the complicated etymology of "adiabatic".
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] Quantum mechanics and quantum statistical mechanics, however, use the word *adiabatic* in a very different sense, one that can at times seem almost opposite to the classical thermodynamic sense.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] In quantum theory, the word *adiabatic* can mean something perhaps near isentropic, or perhaps near quasi-static, but the usage of the word is very different between the two disciplines.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] On the one hand, in quantum theory, if a perturbative element of compressive work is done almost infinitely slowly (that is to say quasi-statically), it is said to have been done *adiabatically*.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] The idea is that the shapes of the eigenfunctions change slowly and continuously, so that no quantum jump is triggered, and the change is virtually reversible.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] While the occupation numbers are unchanged, nevertheless there is change in the energy levels of one-to-one corresponding, pre- and post-compression, eigenstates.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] Thus a perturbative element of work has been done without heat transfer and without introduction of random change within the system.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] In that theory, such a rapid change is said not to be *adiabatic*, and the contrary word *diabatic* is applied to it.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] Recent research suggests that the power absorbed from the perturbation corresponds to the rate of these non-adiabatic transitions.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] This corresponds to the classical process of energy transfer in the form of heat, but with the relative time scales reversed in the quantum case.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] Quantum adiabatic processes occur over relatively long time scales, while classical adiabatic processes occur over relatively short time scales.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] It should also be noted that the concept of 'heat' (in reference to the quantity of thermal energy transferred) breaks down at the quantum level, and the specific form of energy (typically electromagnetic) must be considered instead.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] The small or negligible absorption of energy from the perturbation in a quantum adiabatic process provides a good justification for identifying it as the quantum analogue of adiabatic processes in classical thermodynamics, and for the reuse of the term.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] In classical thermodynamics, such a rapid change would still be called adiabatic because the system is adiabatically isolated, and there is no transfer of energy as heat.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] The strong irreversibility of the change, due to viscosity or other entropy production, does not impinge on this classical usage.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] Thus for a mass of gas, in macroscopic thermodynamics, words are so used that a compression is sometimes loosely or approximately said to be adiabatic if it is rapid enough to avoid significant heat transfer, even if the system is not adiabatically isolated.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] But in quantum statistical theory, a compression is not called adiabatic if it is rapid, even if the system is adiabatically isolated in the classical thermodynamic sense of the term.
[src:carnot-cycle/adiabatic-process] The words are used differently in the two disciplines, as stated just above.
[src:carnot-cycle/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] "**An Inquiry Concerning the Source of the Heat Which Is Excited by Friction**" is a scientific paper by Benjamin Thompson, Count Rumford, which was published in the Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society in 1798.
[src:carnot-cycle/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] The paper provided a substantial challenge to established theories of heat, and began the 19th century revolution in thermodynamics.
[src:carnot-cycle/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] Rumford was an opponent of the caloric theory of heat which held that heat is a fluid that could be neither created nor destroyed.
[src:carnot-cycle/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] He had further developed the view that all gases and liquids are absolute non-conductors of heat.
[src:carnot-cycle/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] His views were out of step with the accepted science of the time and the latter theory had particularly been attacked by John Dalton and John Leslie.
[src:carnot-cycle/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] Rumford was heavily influenced by the argument from design and it is likely that he wished to grant water a privileged and providential status in the regulation of human life.
[src:carnot-cycle/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] Though Rumford was to come to associate heat with motion, there is no evidence that he was committed to the kinetic theory or the principle of *vis viva*.
[src:carnot-cycle/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] In his 1798 paper, Rumford acknowledged that he had predecessors in the notion that heat was a form of motion.
[src:carnot-cycle/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] Those predecessors included Francis Bacon, Robert Boyle, Robert Hooke, John Locke, and Henry Cavendish.
[src:carnot-cycle/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] Rumford had observed the frictional heat generated by boring out cannon barrels at the arsenal in Munich.
[src:carnot-cycle/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] At that time, cannons were cast at the foundry with an extra section of metal forward of what would become the muzzle, and this section was removed and discarded later in the manufacturing process.
[src:carnot-cycle/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] Rumford took an unfinished cannon and modified this section to allow it to be enclosed by a watertight box while a blunted boring tool was used on it.
[src:carnot-cycle/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] He showed that water in this box could be boiled within roughly two and a half hours, and that the supply of frictional heat was seemingly inexhaustible.
[src:carnot-cycle/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] Rumford confirmed that no physical change had taken place in the material of the cannon by comparing the specific heats of the material machined away and that remaining were the same.
[src:carnot-cycle/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] Rumford also argued that the seemingly indefinite generation of heat was incompatible with the caloric theory.
[src:carnot-cycle/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] He contended that the only thing communicated to the barrel was motion.
[src:carnot-cycle/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] Rumford made no attempt to further quantify the heat generated or to measure the mechanical equivalent of heat.
[src:carnot-cycle/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] Most established scientists, such as William Henry, as well as Thomas Thomson, believed that there was enough uncertainty in the caloric theory to allow its adaptation to account for the new results.
[src:carnot-cycle/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] It had certainly proved robust and adaptable up to that time.
[src:carnot-cycle/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] Furthermore, Thomson, Jöns Jakob Berzelius, and Antoine César Becquerel observed that electricity could be indefinitely generated by friction.
[src:carnot-cycle/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] No educated scientist of the time was willing to hold that electricity was not a fluid.
[src:carnot-cycle/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] Ultimately, Rumford's claim of the "inexhaustible" supply of heat was a reckless extrapolation from the study.
[src:carnot-cycle/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] Charles Haldat made some penetrating criticisms of the reproducibility of Rumford's results and it is possible to see the whole experiment as somewhat tendentious.
[src:carnot-cycle/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] However, the experiment inspired the work of James Prescott Joule in the 1840s.
[src:carnot-cycle/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] Joule's more exact measurements were pivotal in establishing the kinetic theory at the expense of caloric.
[src:carnot-cycle/atkinson-cycle] The **Atkinson-cycle engine** is a type of internal combustion engine invented by James Atkinson in 1882.
[src:carnot-cycle/atkinson-cycle] The Atkinson cycle is designed to provide efficiency at the expense of power density.
[src:carnot-cycle/atkinson-cycle] A variation of this approach is used in some modern automobile engines.
[src:carnot-cycle/atkinson-cycle] While originally seen exclusively in hybrid electric applications such as the earlier-generation Toyota Prius, later hybrids and some non-hybrid vehicles now feature engines with variable valve timing.
[src:carnot-cycle/atkinson-cycle] Variable valve timing can run in the Atkinson cycle as a part-time operating regimen, giving good economy while running in Atkinson cycle mode, and conventional power density when running in conventional Otto cycle mode.
[src:carnot-cycle/atkinson-cycle] Atkinson produced three different designs that had a short compression stroke and a longer expansion stroke.
[src:carnot-cycle/atkinson-cycle] The first Atkinson-cycle engine, the *differential engine*, used opposed pistons.
[src:carnot-cycle/atkinson-cycle] The second and best-known design was the *cycle engine*, which used an over-center arm to create four piston strokes in one crankshaft revolution.
[src:carnot-cycle/atkinson-cycle] This unusual reciprocating engine had the intake, compression, power, and exhaust strokes of the four-stroke cycle in a single turn of the crankshaft, and was designed to avoid infringing certain patents covering Otto-cycle engines.
[src:carnot-cycle/atkinson-cycle] Atkinson's third and final engine, the *utilite engine*, operated much like a two-stroke engine.
[src:carnot-cycle/atkinson-cycle] Apart from the features implemented to avoid Otto patents, the truly unique Atkinson's design is that the engines have an expansion stroke that is longer than the compression stroke, and by this method the engine achieves greater thermal efficiency than a traditional piston engine.
[src:carnot-cycle/atkinson-cycle] Atkinson's engines were produced by the British Gas Engine Company and also licensed to other overseas manufacturers.
[src:carnot-cycle/atkinson-cycle] Many modern engines now use a crankshaft center-line offset from the cylinder center-line (making them desaxe engines) and/or unconventional valve timing to produce the effect of a shorter compression stroke/longer power stroke.
[src:carnot-cycle/atkinson-cycle] Miller applied this technique to the four-stroke engine, so it is sometimes referred as the Atkinson/Miller cycle, US patent 2817322 dated Dec 24, 1957.
[src:carnot-cycle/atkinson-cycle] In 1888, Charon filed a French patent and displayed an engine at the Paris Exhibition in 1889.
[src:carnot-cycle/atkinson-cycle] The Charon gas engine (four-stroke) used a similar cycle to Miller, but without a supercharger.
[src:carnot-cycle/atkinson-cycle] It is referred to as the "Charon cycle".
[src:carnot-cycle/atkinson-cycle] Hugo Güldner argued in his 1914 book that Körting was the first firm to build a gas engine with a short compression stroke and a longer expansion phase in 1891, based on a design first proposed by Otto Köhler in 1887.
[src:carnot-cycle/atkinson-cycle] This engine also had an engine-load dependent valve train which increased the intake and compression stroke with increasing engine load.
[src:carnot-cycle/atkinson-cycle] On the other hand, the compression was decreasing at low and medium loads, which ultimately reduced the efficiency.
[src:carnot-cycle/atkinson-cycle] Roy Fedden, at Bristol, tested an arrangement in the Bristol Jupiter IV engine in 1928, with variable retard timing allowing part of the charge to be blown back into the intake manifold, in order to have sustainable reduced operation pressures during takeoff.
[src:carnot-cycle/atkinson-cycle] Modern engine designers are realizing the potential fuel-efficiency improvements the Atkinson-type cycle can provide.
[src:carnot-cycle/atkinson-cycle] The first implementation of the Atkinson cycle was in 1882; unlike later versions, it was arranged as an opposed-piston engine, the Atkinson differential engine.
[src:carnot-cycle/atkinson-cycle] Thus, in each revolution, one piston provided a compression stroke and a power stroke, and then the other piston provided an exhaust stroke and a charging stroke.
[src:carnot-cycle/atkinson-cycle] The next engine designed by Atkinson in 1887 was named the "Cycle Engine" This engine used poppet valves, a cam, and an over-center arm to produce four piston strokes for every revolution of the crankshaft.
[src:carnot-cycle/atkinson-cycle] The intake and compression strokes were significantly shorter than the expansion and exhaust strokes.
[src:carnot-cycle/atkinson-cycle] The "Cycle" engines were produced and sold for several years by the British Engine Company.
[src:carnot-cycle/atkinson-cycle] Atkinson also licensed production to other manufacturers.
[src:carnot-cycle/atkinson-cycle] Sizes ranged from a few up to 100 horsepower.
[src:carnot-cycle/atkinson-cycle] Atkinson's third design was named the "Utilite Engine".
[src:carnot-cycle/atkinson-cycle] Atkinson's "Cycle" engine was efficient; however, its linkage was difficult to balance for high speed operation.
[src:carnot-cycle/atkinson-cycle] Atkinson realized an improvement was needed to make his cycle more applicable as a higher-speed engine.
[src:carnot-cycle/atkinson-cycle] The Utilite operates much like a standard two-stroke except that the exhaust port is located at about the middle of the stroke.
[src:carnot-cycle/atkinson-cycle] During the expansion/power stroke, a cam-operated valve (which remains closed until the piston nears the end of the stroke) prevents pressure from escaping as the piston moves past the exhaust port.
[src:carnot-cycle/atkinson-cycle] The exhaust valve is opened near the bottom of the stroke; it remains open as the piston heads back toward compression, letting fresh air charge the cylinder and exhaust escape until the port is covered by the piston.
[src:carnot-cycle/atkinson-cycle] After the exhaust port is covered the piston begins to compress the remaining air in the cylinder.
[src:carnot-cycle/atkinson-cycle] A small piston fuel pump injects liquid during compression.
[src:carnot-cycle/atkinson-cycle] The ignition source was likely a hot tube as in Atkinson's other engines.
[src:carnot-cycle/atkinson-cycle] This design resulted in a two-stroke engine with a short compression and longer expansion stroke.
[src:carnot-cycle/atkinson-cycle] The Utilite Engine tested as even more efficient than Atkinson's previous "differential" and "cycle" designs.
[src:carnot-cycle/atkinson-cycle] Very few were produced, and none are known to survive.
[src:carnot-cycle/atkinson-cycle] No US patent for the Utilite Engine is known.
[src:carnot-cycle/atkinson-cycle] In the late 20th century, the term "Atkinson cycle" began to be used to describe a modified Otto-cycle engine—in which the intake valve is held open longer than normal, allowing a reverse flow of intake air into the intake manifold.
[src:carnot-cycle/atkinson-cycle] This "simulated" Atkinson cycle is most notably used in the Toyota 1NZ-FXE engine from the early Prius and the Toyota Dynamic Force engines.
[src:carnot-cycle/atkinson-cycle] The effective compression ratio is reduced—for the time the air is escaping the cylinder freely rather than being compressed—but the *expansion* ratio is unchanged (i.e., the compression ratio is smaller than the expansion ratio).
[src:carnot-cycle/atkinson-cycle] The goal of the modern Atkinson cycle is to make the pressure in the combustion chamber at the end of the power stroke equal to atmospheric pressure.
[src:carnot-cycle/atkinson-cycle] When this occurs, all available energy has been obtained from the combustion process.
[src:carnot-cycle/atkinson-cycle] For any given portion of air, the greater expansion ratio converts more energy from heat to useful mechanical energy—meaning the engine is more efficient.
[src:carnot-cycle/atkinson-cycle] The disadvantage of the four-stroke Atkinson-cycle engine versus the more common Otto-cycle engine is reduced power density.
[src:carnot-cycle/atkinson-cycle] Due to a smaller portion of the compression stroke being devoted to compressing the intake air, an Atkinson-cycle engine does not take in as much air as would a similarly designed and sized Otto-cycle engine.
[src:carnot-cycle/atkinson-cycle] Four-stroke engines of this type that use the same type of intake valve motion but also utilize forced induction to make up for the loss of power density are known as Miller-cycle engines.
[src:carnot-cycle/atkinson-cycle] The Atkinson cycle can be used in a rotary engine.
[src:carnot-cycle/atkinson-cycle] In this configuration, an increase in both power and efficiency can be achieved when compared to the Otto cycle.
[src:carnot-cycle/atkinson-cycle] This type of engine retains the one power phase per revolution, together with the different compression and expansion volumes of the original Atkinson cycle.
[src:carnot-cycle/atkinson-cycle] Exhaust gases are expelled from the engine by compressed-air scavenging.
[src:carnot-cycle/atkinson-cycle] This modification of the Atkinson cycle allows the use of alternative fuels such as diesel and hydrogen.
[src:carnot-cycle/atkinson-cycle] Disadvantages of this design include the requirement that rotor tips seal very tightly on the outer housing wall and the mechanical losses suffered through friction between rapidly oscillating parts of irregular shape.
[src:carnot-cycle/atkinson-cycle] See *§ External links* below for more information.
[src:carnot-cycle/atkinson-cycle] While a modified Otto-cycle piston engine using the Atkinson cycle provides good fuel efficiency, it is at the expense of a lower power-per-displacement as compared to a traditional four-stroke engine.
[src:carnot-cycle/atkinson-cycle] If demand for more power is intermittent, the power of the engine can be supplemented by an electric motor during times when more power is needed.
[src:carnot-cycle/atkinson-cycle] This forms the basis of an Atkinson cycle-based hybrid electric drivetrain.
[src:carnot-cycle/atkinson-cycle] These electric motors can be used independently of, or in combination with, the Atkinson-cycle engine, to provide the most efficient means of producing the desired power.
[src:carnot-cycle/atkinson-cycle] This drive-train first entered production in late 1997 in the first-generation Toyota Prius.
[src:carnot-cycle/atkinson-cycle] The 1887 patent (US 367496) describes the mechanical linkages necessary to obtain all four strokes of the four-stroke cycle for a gas engine within one revolution of the crankshaft.
[src:carnot-cycle/atkinson-cycle] There is also a reference to an 1886 Atkinson patent (US 336505), which describes an opposed-piston gas engine.
[src:carnot-cycle/atkinson-cycle] The British patent for the "Utilite'" is from 1892 (#2492).
[src:carnot-cycle/benjamin-thompson] Colonel **Sir Benjamin Thompson, Count Rumford**, FRS (26 March 1753 – 21 August 1814), was an American-born British military officer, scientist and inventor.
[src:carnot-cycle/benjamin-thompson] Born in Woburn, Massachusetts, he supported the Loyalist cause during the American War of Independence, commanding the King's American Dragoons during the conflict.
[src:carnot-cycle/benjamin-thompson] After the war ended in 1783, Thompson moved to London, where he was recognised for his administrative talents and received a knighthood from George III in 1784.
[src:carnot-cycle/benjamin-thompson] A prolific scientist and inventor, Thompson also created several new warship designs.
[src:carnot-cycle/benjamin-thompson] He subsequently moved to the Electorate of Bavaria and entered into the employ of the Bavarian government, heavily reorganising the Bavarian Army.
[src:carnot-cycle/benjamin-thompson] Thompson was rewarded for his efforts by being made an Imperial Count in 1792 before dying in Paris in 1814.
[src:carnot-cycle/benjamin-thompson] Thompson was born in rural Woburn, in the Province of Massachusetts Bay, on 26 March 1753; his birthplace is preserved as a museum.
[src:carnot-cycle/benjamin-thompson] He was educated mainly at the village school, although he sometimes walked almost ten miles to Cambridge with the older Loammi Baldwin to attend lectures by Professor John Winthrop of Harvard College.
[src:carnot-cycle/benjamin-thompson] At the age of 13 he was apprenticed to John Appleton, a merchant of nearby Salem.
[src:carnot-cycle/benjamin-thompson] Thompson excelled at his trade, and coming in contact with refined and well educated people for the first time, adopted many of their characteristics including an interest in science.
[src:carnot-cycle/benjamin-thompson] While recuperating in Woburn in 1769 from an injury, Thompson conducted his first experiments studying the nature of heat and began to correspond with Baldwin and others about them.
[src:carnot-cycle/benjamin-thompson] Later that year he worked several months for a Boston shopkeeper and then apprenticed himself briefly, and unsuccessfully, to a doctor in Woburn.
[src:carnot-cycle/benjamin-thompson] Thompson's prospects were dim in 1772 but in that year they changed abruptly.
[src:carnot-cycle/benjamin-thompson] He met, charmed and married a rich and well-connected widow, an heiress named Sarah Rolfe (née Walker).
[src:carnot-cycle/benjamin-thompson] Her father was a minister, and her late husband left her property at Rumford, Province of New Hampshire, which is today in the modern city of Concord.
[src:carnot-cycle/benjamin-thompson] They moved to Portsmouth, and through his wife's influence with the governor, he was appointed a major in the New Hampshire Militia.
[src:carnot-cycle/benjamin-thompson] Their child (also named Sarah) was born in 1774.
[src:carnot-cycle/benjamin-thompson] Following the outbreak of the American Revolutionary War in 1775, Thompson, by now a wealthy and influential landowner, came out as a Loyalist.
[src:carnot-cycle/benjamin-thompson] He was soon using his connections in the colonial militia to recruit and arm Loyalists seeking to fight alongside the British against rebel forces, which earned him the enmity of Patriots in New Hampshire.
[src:carnot-cycle/benjamin-thompson] Thompson was stripped of his militia commission and a Patriot mob attacked and burned down his house, causing him to flee to British lines, abandoning his wife in the process.
[src:carnot-cycle/benjamin-thompson] He became a political and military advisor to General Thomas Gage (to whom Thompson was already passing information on Patriots), and later assisted Lord George Germain in organizing and provisioning Loyalist military units.
[src:carnot-cycle/benjamin-thompson] In 1781, Thompson raised his own military unit, the King's American Dragoons, which was primarily stationed on Long Island in 1782 and early 1783, where they became notorious for demolishing a church and burial ground in order to erect Fort Golgotha in Huntington, New York.
[src:carnot-cycle/benjamin-thompson] During his military career, Thompson conducted experiments to measure the force of gunpowder, the results of which were widely acclaimed when published in 1781 in the *Philosophical Transactions* of the Royal Society.
[src:carnot-cycle/benjamin-thompson] In 1779, he was elected a Fellow of the Royal Society In 1780 Thompson was appointed as Under-Secretary of the Northern Department in the British Government.
[src:carnot-cycle/benjamin-thompson] But he left abruptly in the following year and traveled to North America as Lieutenant Colonel of the King's American Dragoons.
[src:carnot-cycle/benjamin-thompson] When the American Revolutionary War came to an end, he returned to England and successfully applied to become full colonel.
[src:carnot-cycle/benjamin-thompson] In 1783 he had a portrait painted of himself by Thomas Gainsborough, which is now on display in the Fogg Art Museum.
[src:carnot-cycle/benjamin-thompson] On 23 February 1784, George III conferred upon him the honor of knighthood.
[src:carnot-cycle/benjamin-thompson] In 1785, he moved to Bavaria where he became an *aide-de-camp* to the Prince-elector Charles Theodore.
[src:carnot-cycle/benjamin-thompson] He spent eleven years in Bavaria, reorganizing the army and establishing workhouses for the poor.
[src:carnot-cycle/benjamin-thompson] He also invented Rumford's Soup, a soup for the poor, and established the cultivation of the potato in Bavaria.
[src:carnot-cycle/benjamin-thompson] He studied methods of cooking, heating, and lighting, including the relative costs and efficiencies of wax candles, tallow candles, and oil lamps.
[src:carnot-cycle/benjamin-thompson] On Prince Charles' behalf he created the Englischer Garten in Munich in 1789; it remains today and is known as one of the largest urban public parks in the world.
[src:carnot-cycle/benjamin-thompson] He was elected a Foreign Honorary Member of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences in 1789.
[src:carnot-cycle/benjamin-thompson] For his efforts, in 1791 Thompson was made an Imperial Count, becoming *Reichsgraf von Rumford*.
[src:carnot-cycle/benjamin-thompson] He took the name "Rumford" after the town of Rumford, New Hampshire, which was an older name for Concord where he had been married.
[src:carnot-cycle/benjamin-thompson] His experiments on gunnery and explosives led to an interest in heat.
[src:carnot-cycle/benjamin-thompson] He devised a method for measuring the specific heat of a solid substance but was disappointed when Johan Wilcke published his parallel discovery first.
[src:carnot-cycle/benjamin-thompson] Thompson next investigated the insulating properties of various materials, including fur, wool and feathers.
[src:carnot-cycle/benjamin-thompson] He correctly deduced that the insulating properties of these natural materials arise from the fact that they inhibit the convection of air.
[src:carnot-cycle/benjamin-thompson] He then inferred — incorrectly — that air and, in fact, all gases, were perfect non-conductors of heat.
[src:carnot-cycle/benjamin-thompson] He further saw this as evidence of the argument from design, contending that divine providence had arranged for fur on animals in such a way as to guarantee their comfort.
[src:carnot-cycle/benjamin-thompson] In 1797, he extended his claim about non-conductivity to liquids.
[src:carnot-cycle/benjamin-thompson] The idea raised considerable objections from the scientific establishment, John Dalton and John Leslie making particularly forthright attacks.
[src:carnot-cycle/benjamin-thompson] Instrumentation far exceeding anything available in terms of accuracy and precision would have been needed to verify Thompson's claim.
[src:carnot-cycle/benjamin-thompson] Again, he seems to have been influenced by his theological beliefs, and historian of science D.
[src:carnot-cycle/benjamin-thompson] Cardwell speculated that Thompson wished to grant water a privileged and providential status in the regulation of human life.
[src:carnot-cycle/benjamin-thompson] He is considered the founder of the sous-vide food preparation method owing to his experiment with a mutton shoulder.
[src:carnot-cycle/benjamin-thompson] He described this method in one of his essays.
[src:carnot-cycle/benjamin-thompson] Rumford's most important scientific work took place in Munich, and centred on the nature of heat, which he contended in "An Inquiry Concerning the Source of the Heat Which Is Excited by Friction" (1798) was not the caloric of then-current scientific thinking but a form of *motion*.
[src:carnot-cycle/benjamin-thompson] Rumford had observed the frictional heat generated by boring cannon at the arsenal in Munich.
[src:carnot-cycle/benjamin-thompson] Rumford immersed a cannon barrel in water and arranged for a specially blunted boring tool.
[src:carnot-cycle/benjamin-thompson] He showed that the water could be boiled within roughly two and a half hours and that the supply of frictional heat was seemingly inexhaustible.
[src:carnot-cycle/benjamin-thompson] Rumford confirmed that no physical change had taken place in the material of the cannon by comparing the specific heats of the material machined away and that remaining.
[src:carnot-cycle/benjamin-thompson] Rumford argued that the seemingly indefinite generation of heat was incompatible with the caloric theory.
[src:carnot-cycle/benjamin-thompson] Though this work met with a hostile reception, it was subsequently important in establishing the laws of conservation of energy later in the 19th century.
[src:carnot-cycle/benjamin-thompson] He explained Pictet's experiment, which demonstrates the reflection of cold, by supposing that all bodies emit invisible rays, undulations in the ethereal fluid.
[src:carnot-cycle/benjamin-thompson] He did experiments to support his theories of calorific and frigorific radiation and said the communication of heat was the net effect of calorific (hot) rays and frigorific (cold) rays and the rays emitted by the object.
[src:carnot-cycle/benjamin-thompson] When an object absorbs radiation from a warmer object (calorific rays) its temperature rises, and when it absorbs radiation from a colder object (frigorific rays) its temperature falls.
[src:carnot-cycle/benjamin-thompson] See note 8, "An enquiry concerning the nature of heat and the mode of its communication" Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society, starting at page 112.
[src:carnot-cycle/benjamin-thompson] Thompson was an active and prolific inventor, developing improvements for chimneys, fireplaces and industrial furnaces, as well as inventing a double boiler, a kitchen range, and a coffee drip-press pot roughly between 1810 and 1814.
[src:carnot-cycle/benjamin-thompson] He invented a percolating coffee pot following his pioneering work with the Bavarian Army, where he improved the diet of the soldiers (Rumford's Soup) as well as their clothes.
[src:carnot-cycle/benjamin-thompson] The Rumford fireplace created a sensation in London when he introduced the idea of restricting the chimney opening to increase the updraught, which was a much more efficient way to heat a room than earlier fireplaces.
[src:carnot-cycle/benjamin-thompson] He and his workers modified fireplaces by inserting bricks into the hearth to make the side walls angled, and added a choke to the chimney to increase the speed of air going up the flue.
[src:carnot-cycle/benjamin-thompson] The effect was to produce a streamlined air flow, so all the smoke would go up into the chimney rather than lingering and entering the room.
[src:carnot-cycle/benjamin-thompson] It also had the effect of increasing the efficiency of the fire, and gave extra control of the rate of combustion of the fuel, whether wood or coal.
[src:carnot-cycle/benjamin-thompson] Many fashionable London houses were modified to his instructions, and became smoke-free.
[src:carnot-cycle/benjamin-thompson] Thomas Jefferson used the Rumford fireplace design at Monticello.
[src:carnot-cycle/benjamin-thompson] Thompson became a celebrity when news of his success spread.
[src:carnot-cycle/benjamin-thompson] His work was also very profitable, and much imitated when he published his analysis of the way chimneys worked.
[src:carnot-cycle/benjamin-thompson] In many ways, he was similar to Benjamin Franklin, who also invented a new kind of heating stove.
[src:carnot-cycle/benjamin-thompson] The retention of heat was a recurring theme in his work, as he is also credited with the invention of thermal underwear.
[src:carnot-cycle/benjamin-thompson] Thompson also significantly improved the design of kilns used to produce quicklime, and Rumford furnaces were soon being constructed throughout Europe.
[src:carnot-cycle/benjamin-thompson] The key innovation involved separating the burning fuel from the limestone, so that the lime produced by the heat of the furnace was not contaminated by ash from the fire.
[src:carnot-cycle/benjamin-thompson] Rumford worked in photometry, the measurement of light.
[src:carnot-cycle/benjamin-thompson] He made a photometer and introduced the standard candle, the predecessor of the candela, as a unit of luminous intensity.
[src:carnot-cycle/benjamin-thompson] His standard candle was made from the oil of a sperm whale, to rigid specifications.
[src:carnot-cycle/benjamin-thompson] He also published studies of "illusory" or subjective complementary colours, induced by the shadows created by two lights, one white and one coloured; these observations were cited and generalized by Michel-Eugène Chevreul as his "law of simultaneous colour contrast" in 1839.
[src:carnot-cycle/benjamin-thompson] After 1799, he divided his time between France and England.
[src:carnot-cycle/benjamin-thompson] With Sir Joseph Banks, he established the Royal Institution of Great Britain in 1799.
[src:carnot-cycle/benjamin-thompson] The pair chose Sir Humphry Davy as the first lecturer.
[src:carnot-cycle/benjamin-thompson] The institution flourished and became world-famous as a result of Davy's pioneering research.
[src:carnot-cycle/benjamin-thompson] His assistant, Michael Faraday, established the Institution as a premier research laboratory, and also justly famous for its series of public lectures popularizing science.
[src:carnot-cycle/benjamin-thompson] That tradition continues to the present, and the Royal Institution Christmas lectures attract large audiences through their TV broadcasts.
[src:carnot-cycle/benjamin-thompson] Thompson endowed the Rumford medals of the Royal Society and the American Academy of Arts and Sciences, and endowed the Rumford Chair of Physics at Harvard University.
[src:carnot-cycle/benjamin-thompson] In 1803, he was elected a foreign member of the Royal Swedish Academy of Sciences, and as a member of the American Philosophical Society.
[src:carnot-cycle/benjamin-thompson] In 1772, Thompson married a rich and well-connected widow, an heiress named Sarah Rolfe (née Walker).
[src:carnot-cycle/benjamin-thompson] Thompson abandoned his American wife, Sarah, at the outbreak of the American Revolution; she died in 1792.
[src:carnot-cycle/benjamin-thompson] After several affairs and a close friendship with Lady Emily (Amelia) Mary Lamb Temple (21 April 1787...11 September 1869), Viscountess Palmerston,(born Mary Mee), in 1804, he married Marie-Anne Lavoisier, the widow of the great French chemist Antoine Lavoisier.
[src:carnot-cycle/benjamin-thompson] Thompson separated from his second wife after three years, but he settled in Paris and continued his scientific work until his death on 21 August 1814.
[src:carnot-cycle/benjamin-thompson] Thompson is buried in the small cemetery of Auteuil in Paris, just across from Adrien-Marie Legendre.
[src:carnot-cycle/benjamin-thompson] Upon his death, his daughter from his first marriage, Sarah Thompson, inherited his title as Countess Rumford.
[src:carnot-cycle/benjamin-thompson] Some periodicals and satirical publications of Rumford’s time made references that associated him with men who were publicly linked to homosexuality, notably George Germain, 1st Viscount Sackville..
[src:carnot-cycle/benjamin-thompson] Rumford’s surviving letters and papers do not contain evidence of same-sex relationships, and no independent contemporary documentation corroborates the claims.
[src:carnot-cycle/benoît-paul-émile-clapeyron] Born in Paris, Clapeyron studied at the École polytechnique, graduating in 1818.
[src:carnot-cycle/benoît-paul-émile-clapeyron] In 1820 he and Gabriel Lamé went to Saint Petersburg to teach and work at the school of public works there.
[src:carnot-cycle/benoît-paul-émile-clapeyron] He returned to Paris only after the Revolution of July 1830, supervising the construction of the first railway lines connecting Paris to Versailles and Paris to Saint-Germain.
[src:carnot-cycle/benoît-paul-émile-clapeyron] The half brothers Stéphane Mony and Eugène Flachat collaborated in this project, which was financed by Adolphe d'Eichthal(fr), Rothschild, Auguste Thurneyssen, Sanson Davillier and the Péreire brothers.
[src:carnot-cycle/benoît-paul-émile-clapeyron] Clapeyron took his steam engine designs to England in 1836 to find a manufacturer and engaged Sharp, Roberts and Co.
[src:carnot-cycle/benoît-paul-émile-clapeyron] From 1844 to 1859 Clapeyron was a professor at École des Ponts et Chaussées.
[src:carnot-cycle/benoît-paul-émile-clapeyron] Clapeyron married Mélanie Bazaine, daughter of Pierre-Dominique Bazaine (mathematician and ingénieur des ponts), and older sister of Pierre-Dominique (Adolphe) Bazaine (railway engineer) and François Achille Bazaine (Marshal of France).
[src:carnot-cycle/benoît-paul-émile-clapeyron] Though Carnot had developed a compelling analysis of a generalised heat engine, he had employed the clumsy and already unfashionable caloric theory.
[src:carnot-cycle/benoît-paul-émile-clapeyron] Clapeyron, in his memoire, presented Carnot's work in a more accessible and analytic graphical form, showing the Carnot cycle as a closed curve on an indicator diagram, a chart of pressure against volume (named in his honor **Clapeyron's graph**).
[src:carnot-cycle/benoît-paul-émile-clapeyron] Clapeyron's analysis of Carnot was more broadly disseminated in 1843 when Johann Poggendorff translated it into German.
[src:carnot-cycle/benoît-paul-émile-clapeyron] These foundations enabled him to make substantive extensions of Clausius' work, including the formula, now known as the Clausius–Clapeyron relation, which characterises the phase transition between two phases of matter.
[src:carnot-cycle/benoît-paul-émile-clapeyron] He further considered questions of phase transitions in what later became known as Stefan problems.
[src:carnot-cycle/benoît-paul-émile-clapeyron] Clapeyron also worked on the characterisation of perfect gases, the equilibrium of homogeneous solids, and calculations of the statics of continuous beams, notably the theorem of three moments (**Clapeyron's theorem**).
[src:carnot-cycle/carnot-cycle] A **Carnot cycle** is an ideal thermodynamic cycle proposed by French physicist Sadi Carnot in 1824 and expanded upon by others in the 1830s and 1840s.
[src:carnot-cycle/carnot-cycle] By Carnot's theorem, it provides an upper limit on the efficiency of any classical thermodynamic engine during the conversion of heat into work, or conversely, the efficiency of a refrigeration system in creating a temperature difference through the application of work to the system.
[src:carnot-cycle/carnot-cycle] In a Carnot cycle, a system or engine transfers energy in the form of heat between two thermal reservoirs at temperatures *T*H and *T*C (referred to as the hot and cold reservoirs, respectively), and a part of this transferred energy is converted to the work done by the system.
[src:carnot-cycle/carnot-cycle] The cycle is reversible, merely transferring thermal energy between the thermal reservoirs and the system without gain or loss.
[src:carnot-cycle/carnot-cycle] When work is applied to the system, heat moves from the cold to hot reservoir (heat pump or refrigeration).
[src:carnot-cycle/carnot-cycle] When heat moves from the hot to the cold reservoir, the system applies work to the environment.
[src:carnot-cycle/carnot-cycle] The work *W* done by the system or engine to the environment per Carnot cycle depends on the temperatures of the thermal reservoirs per cycle such as *W* = *Q*H(*T*H − *T*C)/*T*H, where *Q*H is heat transferred from the hot reservoir to the system per cycle.
[src:carnot-cycle/carnot-cycle] **(reversible adiabatic) expansion of the gas ( work output).** For this step (2 to 3 on **Figure 1**) the gas in the engine is thermally insulated from both the hot and cold reservoirs, thus they neither gain nor lose heat.
[src:carnot-cycle/carnot-cycle] The gas continues to expand with reduction of its pressure, doing work on the surroundings (raising the piston; Stage Two figure, right), and losing an amount of internal energy equal to the work done.
[src:carnot-cycle/carnot-cycle] The loss of internal energy causes the gas to cool.
[src:carnot-cycle/carnot-cycle] In this step it is cooled to a temperature that is infinitesimally higher than the cold reservoir temperature *T*C.
[src:carnot-cycle/carnot-cycle] The gas temperature is infinitesimally higher than *T*C to allow heat transfer from the gas to the cold reservoir.
[src:carnot-cycle/carnot-cycle] There is no change in temperature, it is an isothermal process.
[src:carnot-cycle/carnot-cycle] The surroundings do work on the gas, pushing the piston down (Stage Three figure, right).
[src:carnot-cycle/carnot-cycle] An amount of energy earned by the gas from this work exactly transfers as a heat energy *Q*C < 0 (negative as leaving from the system, according to the universal convention in thermodynamics) to the cold reservoir.
[src:carnot-cycle/carnot-cycle] **Compression.** (4 to 1 on **Figure 1**) Once again the gas in the engine is thermally insulated from the hot and cold reservoirs, and the engine is assumed to be frictionless and the process is slow enough, hence reversible.
[src:carnot-cycle/carnot-cycle] During this step, the surroundings do work on the gas, pushing the piston down further (Stage Four figure, right), increasing its internal energy, compressing it, and causing its temperature to rise back to the temperature infinitesimally less than *T*H due solely to the work added to the system.
[src:carnot-cycle/carnot-cycle] At this point the gas is in the same state as at the start of step 1.
[src:carnot-cycle/carnot-cycle] This is true as *Q*C and *T*C are both smaller in magnitude and in fact are in the same ratio as *Q*H/*T*H.
[src:carnot-cycle/carnot-cycle] When a Carnot cycle is plotted on a pressure–volume diagram (**Figure 1**), the isothermal stages follow the isotherm lines for the working fluid, the adiabatic stages move between isotherms, and the area bounded by the complete cycle path represents the total work that can be done during one cycle.
[src:carnot-cycle/carnot-cycle] From point 1 to 2 and point 3 to 4 the temperature is constant (isothermal process).
[src:carnot-cycle/carnot-cycle] Heat transfer from point 4 to 1 and point 2 to 3 are equal to zero (adiabatic process).
[src:carnot-cycle/carnot-cycle] A Carnot cycle plotted on a Temperature-entropy diagram (**Figure 4**) is rather simple.
[src:carnot-cycle/carnot-cycle] Isothermic paths are horizontal, adiabatic paths are vertical.
[src:carnot-cycle/carnot-cycle] The area enclosed by the cycle is the amount of heat energy extracted from the hot reservoir but not delivered to the cold reservoir, which has been converted into work.
[src:carnot-cycle/carnot-cycle] Defining ΔS = *S*B − *S*A, the heat energy injected into the engine is *Q*H = *T*HΔS and the heat energy extracted from the engine is *Q*C = *T*CΔS, which is the portion of the injected energy that is unavailable to do work.
[src:carnot-cycle/carnot-cycle] The engine is reversibly transporting entropy from the hot reservoir to the cold reservoir.
[src:carnot-cycle/carnot-cycle] This is the Carnot heat engine working efficiency definition as the fraction of the work done by the engine system to the thermal energy received by the system from the hot reservoir per cycle.
[src:carnot-cycle/carnot-cycle] This thermal energy is the cycle initiator.
[src:carnot-cycle/carnot-cycle] A Carnot heat-engine cycle described is a totally reversible cycle.
[src:carnot-cycle/carnot-cycle] That is, all the processes that compose it can be reversed, in which case it becomes the Carnot heat pump and refrigeration cycle.
[src:carnot-cycle/carnot-cycle] This time, the cycle remains exactly the same except that the directions of any heat and work interactions are reversed.
[src:carnot-cycle/carnot-cycle] Heat is absorbed from the low-temperature reservoir, heat is rejected to a high-temperature reservoir, and a work input is required to accomplish all this.
[src:carnot-cycle/carnot-cycle] The *P*–*V* diagram of the reversed Carnot cycle is the same as for the Carnot heat-engine cycle except that the directions of the processes are reversed.
[src:carnot-cycle/carnot-cycle] It can be seen from the above diagram that for any cycle operating between temperatures *T*H and *T*C, none can exceed the efficiency of a Carnot cycle.
[src:carnot-cycle/carnot-cycle] In mesoscopic heat engines, work per cycle of operation in general fluctuates due to thermal noise.
[src:carnot-cycle/carnot-cycle] If the cycle is performed quasi-statically, the fluctuations vanish even on the mesoscale.
[src:carnot-cycle/carnot-cycle] However, if the cycle is performed faster than the relaxation time of the working medium, the fluctuations of work are inevitable.
[src:carnot-cycle/carnot-cycle] Nevertheless, when work and heat fluctuations are counted, an exact equality relates the exponential average of work performed by any heat engine to the heat transfer from the hotter heat bath.
[src:carnot-cycle/carnot-cycle] Carnot realized that, in reality, it is not possible to build a thermodynamically reversible engine.
[src:carnot-cycle/carnot-cycle] So, real heat engines are even less efficient than indicated by Equation **3**.
[src:carnot-cycle/carnot-cycle] In addition, real engines that operate along the Carnot cycle style (isothermal expansion / adiabatic expansion / isothermal compression / adiabatic compression) are rare.
[src:carnot-cycle/carnot-cycle] Nevertheless, Equation **3** is extremely useful for determining the maximum efficiency that could ever be expected for a given set of thermal reservoirs.
[src:carnot-cycle/carnot-cycle] The first prototype of the diesel engine was based on the principles of the Carnot cycle.
[src:carnot-cycle/carnot-cycle] The Carnot heat engine is, ultimately, a theoretical construct based on an *idealized* thermodynamic system.
[src:carnot-cycle/carnot-cycle] On a practical human-scale level the Carnot cycle has proven a valuable model, as in advancing the development of the diesel engine.
[src:carnot-cycle/carnot-cycle] However the requirement of perfect reversibility is unattainable in a practical sense, and, ultimately, a perfect Carnot engine is incapable of doing any work in a finite amount of time.
[src:carnot-cycle/carnot-cycle] As such, per Carnot's theorem, the Carnot engine may be thought as the theoretical limit of macroscopic scale heat engines rather than any practical device that could ever be built.
